      modelAnswer: 'The fluid mosaic model describes the cell membrane as a fluid bilayer through which proteins and other components are distributed like tiles in a mosaic. The bilayer is made of phospholipids: each has a hydrophilic phosphate-glycerol head and two hydrophobic fatty-acid tails. In water, molecules self-assemble into two layers with heads facing the watery environment and tails facing inwards. Cholesterol embedded between phospholipids stabilises fluidity over a range of temperatures. Intrinsic proteins span the bilayer (channels, carriers, receptors); extrinsic proteins on either surface include enzymes, recognition markers and links to the cytoskeleton. Carbohydrates attached to lipids and proteins (glycolipids and glycoproteins) on the outer surface contribute to cell-cell recognition. Functions: selective permeability — the hydrophobic core blocks polar molecules and ions, while channels and carriers control specific transport; signalling — receptors bind hormones or neurotransmitters and trigger cellular responses; recognition — antigens, MHC molecules; cell-cell contact; compartmentalisation — internal membranes (nuclear envelope, ER, Golgi, mitochondrial inner membrane) form discrete compartments; bulk transport — endocytosis and exocytosis. Fluidity is essential: it allows membrane proteins to redistribute, enables cell movement, vesicle trafficking and cell division, and lets membranes self-seal. Membrane composition varies between organelles and tissues, matching specific functions (e.g. high cholesterol in animal plasma membranes, double membranes around mitochondria with cristae). Disorders of membrane proteins (e.g. CFTR in cystic fibrosis, dystrophin in muscular dystrophy) cause major disease, illustrating how function depends on the right components in the right place. The fluid mosaic model is supported by freeze-fracture microscopy, FRAP experiments showing lateral diffusion, and biochemical analysis of membrane components — and remains the foundation of modern membrane biology.'
