      q: 'Compare the use of recombinant DNA technology in producing therapeutic proteins, and assess the ethical and practical issues involved.',
      marks: 16, command: 'Compare',
      modelAnswer: 'Recombinant DNA technology allows a gene from one organism to be inserted into another so that the recipient produces the protein of interest. The gene is identified, isolated (often by reverse-transcribing mRNA to cDNA, avoiding introns), cut from its source with restriction enzymes, joined to a vector (plasmid) using DNA ligase, and introduced into a host cell — bacteria (E. coli), yeast or mammalian cells. Cells that have taken up the vector are identified using marker genes and grown in fermenters; the protein is then extracted and purified. Compare: bacterial systems are cheap, fast and high-yielding but cannot perform many post-translational modifications (glycosylation, complex disulphide bond formation), so are best for simple proteins (e.g. insulin). Yeast can do some modifications, costs are still moderate, growth is fast. Mammalian cells (CHO, HEK293) are needed for proteins requiring complex modifications (clotting factors, monoclonal antibodies) but are expensive and slower. Transgenic plants and animals can also be used (e.g. milk from transgenic goats containing therapeutic proteins). Examples include human insulin (replacing pig insulin and avoiding allergy), human growth hormone (replacing risky pituitary extract), clotting factors for haemophilia, erythropoietin, and monoclonal antibodies for cancer and autoimmune disease. Benefits: large-scale, consistent production of human proteins free of pathogens; lower long-term costs; the ability to make rare or animal-unsuitable proteins; abundant supply for global health. Practical issues: bacterial cells may not fold proteins correctly or perform necessary modifications; protein purification must reach pharmaceutical standards; fermentation must be scaled and monitored; product stability and cold-chain logistics matter for delivery, especially in low-resource settings. Ethical issues: animal welfare in transgenic systems and testing; biosafety concerns about engineered organisms escaping into the environment; patents that can make life-saving drugs unaffordable in poorer countries (insulin pricing controversy); broader debate about genetic modification of animals and plants for human benefit. The use of human cells (e.g. HeLa) raises further questions about consent. Religious and philosophical concerns include "playing God" and the rights of organisms. Strong regulation, transparent testing, public engagement, equitable access and ongoing dialogue between scientists, ethicists and policy-makers are essential. Recombinant DNA technology has transformed medicine by providing safe, abundant therapeutic proteins, but cost, equity and welfare considerations demand continued attention as new applications and host systems emerge.'
